            <h2>Psychoeducational and Neuropsychological Evaluations</h2>
            <p> 
                <strong>
                    Which Evaluation Should I Choose for My Child?
                </strong>
            </p>
            <p>
                The choice of evaluations depends on the referral question. A neuropsychological evaluation is usually preferred when diagnostic information and intervention guidance are needed. When a child has already been diagnosed with a learning disability and only needs documentation for accommodations in school (such as extended time on tests), then a psychoeducational evaluation can be sufficient.
            </p>
            <p>
                <h3>Assessment Options</h3>
            </p>
            <div class="assessment-card-wrapper">
              <div class="assessment-card">
                <h3>Psychoeducational Assessment</h3>
                <p>A psychoeducational assessment is a comprehensive evaluation of cognitive abilities, academic skills, and social-emotional functioning to understand a person's learning profile and identify strengths and challenges. Psychoeducational evaluations quantify difficulties in reading, writing, and math, helping to qualify students for school services and accommodations like extended test time.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="assessment-card">
                <h3>Neuropsychological Evaluation</h3>
                <p>A comprehensive evaluation, providing deeper insights into the neurocognitive processes affecting learning and designed to determine the 'why' behind academic short-comings. The psychoeducational evaluation is part of a broader neuropsychological evaluation in school-age children. Neuropsychological evaluations provide more in-depth analysis of areas such as language, visual-perceptual skills, information processing, attention/executive functioning, memory, and psycho-emotional health.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="assessment-card">
                <h3>DSM Diagnostic Assessments</h3>
                <p>People seek a DSM diagnosis to better understand their symptoms, receive appropriate treatment recommendations, and to access support services or accommodations that can improve their quality of life.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="assessment-card">
                <h3>ADHD and Executive Functioning Assessment</h3>
                <p>An ADHD and executive functioning assessment is conducted to evaluate attention, impulse control, organization, working memory, and other cognitive skills that impact daily functioning. The results help determine if symptoms are consistent with ADHD and guide appropriate interventions, accommodations, or treatment planning.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="assessment-card">
                <h3>Behavioral and Social-Emotional Assessments</h3>
                <p>A behavioral or social-emotional assessment helps identify challenges such as anxiety, depression, mood disorders, attention difficulties, or emotional regulation issues. The results guide appropriate interventions and support planning at home and in school.</p>
              </div>
              <div class="assessment-card">
                <h3>Independent Educational Evaluation (IEE)</h3>
                <p>An IEE is an assessment by a qualified professional who is not employed by the school district. Parents have the legal right under the Individuals with Disabilities Education Act (IDEA) to request an IEE if they disagree with the school’s evaluation - especially if they feel it was incomplete, inaccurate, or doesn’t reflect their child’s needs. If approved, parents can select their own outside evaluator for a new, unbiased assessment.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
        </div>

